Over the last few years, I&rsquo;ve heard a lot of people talk about curriculum.
&ldquo;We need a curriculum that works for everyone.&rdquo;
&ldquo;If we had a good curriculum, we could get CS in the schools.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Can&rsquo;t you just take someone else&rsquo;s curriculum and scale things out?&rdquo;
People miss the point. In my twenty some odd years as an educator and my forty five as a human (including 18 as a parent), I&rsquo;ve never heard someone talk about that one inspirational curriculum that made all the difference in their lives.

The Problem: The buzz word is &ldquo;accountability.&rdquo; Why are teachers special? Why don&rsquo;t they feel they need to be evaluated like other professionals? Why do they feel they need a &ldquo;job for life?&rdquo;
Of course, the job for life line is nonsense &ndash; teachers have tenure, but that&rsquo;s just due process - not a guarantee of a job.
Friends in the private sector ask &ldquo;if a teacher is doing a good job, why do they need tenure?
